Text.Value: I'm writing an account of your glorious victory.
I didn't ask anyone to write my story.
You have something in mind?
Quite a display that was - usually I'm the one providing the drama on nights such as these.

EditorData.NodeContext: Laden with schadenfreude - we just had a public dalliance with a woman he considers psychotic, and she very nearly killed us afterwards.
EditorData.logicalname: Character still around after Drow Betrayal

Text.Value: Who locked you up?
Here - you can keep that copy. The details are very much burned into my memory.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Handing us his notes from his inventory (off-screen)

Text.Value: I need the goblins to believe I'm on their side.
No, your actions in the grove were most heroic, but I am afraid this a matter of style, not sentiment.
I must deliberate. Go - enjoy your evening! I shall have work for you in the days to come.
First - you'll need a name.
My friend, I am engaged in celebration in its purest form - commemoration.
Why - your naming, quite obviously.
'Worth'? Volothamp Geddarm takes the matters of names most seriously.
Ah, well - no need to involve your guests, I should think.
Not to belittle your achievements to date, of course! But besting a dragon, a giant, a god perhaps... hmm.
...Perhaps I spoke in haste. Your insights would, of course, be most welcome.
Open the cage.
It seems that following one story has tipped me head-long into another - yours. And I truly can't wait to write it.
And yet I found it nonetheless. Such is the nature of Volothamp Geddarm, author and interrogator of mysteries.
I am simply saying that you are a creature of ambition. Drive. Intent.
Excuse me - who are you?
Don't you have anything of actual worth to work on?
...Actually slaying a dragon would prove quite helpful, mind.
'Goblinsbane' has a nice ring to it.
I can't rightly document your deeds from the bottom of a goblin cookpot, after all. Ha ha.
A wonderful one indeed - but your deeds loom larger than life now, my friend. You simply must have a title to match.
Of course you didn't. History is but a series of accidents, after all, both happy and heinous.
Maybe I'll keep you in this cage for good.
Fine. Keep your scribbles.
But how am I to ensure your most-deserved renown without a suitably thrilling title?
I know you had a purpose. Though I'll grant that I'm quite in the dark as to what it was. Might you elaborate?

EditorData.NodeContext: Innocently asking the player why they have committed a mass killing of innocent civlians - as if idly curious

Text.Value: Ah, a ruse! You've played the part admirably, if I may say so.

EditorData.NodeContext: Voice lowered; he's in on the secret.

Text.Value: What about 'Grovekeeper'?
But I'd rather talk about you. If I'm to write an account of the battle, I'll need details while they're still sticky.
After all, I'm quite certain I once saw one expire from the strain of spelling his own name.
No, no - it is for you to slay the dragons, and for me to worry about the accolades.
No, I'm afraid that won't do. You shall simply have to go out and slay something decidedly more dramatic.
I don't remember inviting you to my camp.
You should get some rest. You've had such a big day.

EditorData.NodeContext: Falsely congratulatory - we've committed an atrocity in his eyes and have forced him to be at the celebration.

Text.Value: I do hope you didn't catch anything. I'm sure an itching conscience is quite enough.

EditorData.NodeContext: Very clearly false concern - he considers us scum for allying with this woman in the first place, and thinks we deserve whatever we get

Text.Value: Something iconic, but not too much of a mouthful. We don't want to exclude the common-folk, after all. I intend this tale to enrapture all.
How did you get here?
That way, perhaps we'll both survive the night.
These beasts appear quite convinced that you're a comrade in arms. Just as the tieflings were, I expect.

EditorData.NodeContext: this is thick with meaning. He's subtley admonishing you for doublecrossing the tieflings.

Text.Value: Volothamp Geddarm - realm-renowned author, auteur and now, it appears, very much your captive.
I have other things to do.
It's simply that, for the life of me, I cannot imagine what that purpose was. Could you elaborate?

EditorData.NodeContext: Innocently asking the player why they have committed a mass killing of innocent civlians - as if idly curious

Text.Value: Far too much - this is the very problem. If you could set aside your many triumphs, carry out one defining act...
The very heart of my dilemma! You are the do-er of deeds, I the mere chronicler.
I get it. Something flashy and made up, like 'Volothamp Geddarm'.
See your guests aren't bored. The last thing we want is for them to make their own fun.
But I daresay you're committed now, my friend. So chin up, look around, and remember your role, hm?

EditorData.NodeContext: With an edge. Volo is encouraging you but he also thinks you're a war criminal.

Text.Value: Ah, the guest of honour arrives! I've been observing the festivities from a sensible distance.
Back to your revelry, then - when I have crafted your legend for you, no doubt you shall hear of it.
You make that sound like a threat.
I'd heard tell of a goblin camp that had been overtaken by some new upstart god.
'Grovekeeper'? Are you a gardener? We aim to cultivate mystery, not... shrubbery.
I'd rather no one knew.
Ye gods, then let us add ignorance to your list of crimes. I am Volothamp Geddarm, realm-renowned author, auteur, and tastemaker.
And the goblins? Should I tell them what you're writing?
And he has an arsenal of choice names for those who don't.
If you are to repay what you owe, then there is no time to waste. Start at the beginning.

EditorData.NodeContext: Getting on with business, not taking time for us to catch up (we have no idea who this man is)

Text.Value: If we are to write your legend in the stars, then we must first give you a name.
Aha, there you are! Come now, settle in.
I didn't mean for any of this to happen.
It is for Kelemvor to judge you, when the time comes. May he do so justly.

EditorData.NodeContext: Kelemvor is the god of the afterlife - being judged justly is not something the player would enjoy, in Volo's opinion

Text.Value: The unenlightened might see your actions there as no more than aimless slaughter.

EditorData.NodeContext: Volo is laying it on thick. He hates you but wants the scoop so he's playing devil's advocate

Text.Value: I do hope you have partaken of something bracing? This may well take us all night.
But rest assured that your story is in safe hands. Volothamp Geddarm knows exactly what you are.

EditorData.NodeContext: A hint of distaste to his usual enthusiasm, but not enough to cause overt offense.

Text.Value: When I came to investigate, they invited me to stay. Rather permanently.
Back to the revelry with you! I'll give the matter some thought in small council.
Not to meddle in your side of this partnership, but slaying goblins is not exactly the stuff of legends, is it?
What you did at the grove... I rather think the world should remember, don't you?

EditorData.NodeContext: Volo thinks the player is a real villain. This should have the weight of 'don't you want your atrocities recorded?'

Text.Value: You stole a story from me. Courtesy demands I get yours in return.

EditorData.NodeContext: As if repeating a grave rule of his profession that should be self-evident to anyone.

Text.Value: I don't need to justify myself to you.
I appreciate your editorial instincts, but Deneir himself does not get a peek at my early drafts.
And by 'this', you mean...?
Now, back to your revels. I have some details of your victory to rearrange.
Don't you want to join in the celebrations?
Shouldn't we be celebrating?
And do you think Volothamp Geddarm got where he did by waiting to be asked?
Of course not! I am only here to bear witness.
My next piece was meant to be an expos on the local goblins and their 'Absolute'.
Fear not! I am content - and quite forgotten - where I am. Better in a cell than in a stew, what?
What a fun friend you've made.

EditorData.NodeContext: Falsely congratulatory. - he considers us scum for allying with this woman in the first place, and thinks we deserve whatever we get

Text.Value: The grove, for example. Its destruction was quite necessary to your purpose, I have no doubt.
Aha, there you are! Come now, settle in.
Should my writing favour facts over form, it is only to keep pace with events.
You have been quite busy, after all.
I have no doubt! But such grand deeds as yours often require... interpretation. The grove, for example.
Volothamp Geddarm - realm-renowned author, auteur, and tastemaker.
Give me your notes. I'll decide what you write.
I already have a name.
Exac-tly wrong, my friend! I urge you to leave the fact-finding to experts, hmm?

EditorData.NodeContext: He was about ot say 'Exactly!' and confirm the player's claim, but hten remembered he should NOT reveal that to the player and tries to backpedal.

Text.Value: Leave.
That ballad was but a crude preview, a frame without its crowning jewel - your nom de guerre.

EditorData.logicalname: FLAG FOR BALLAD HAVING OCCURED (IE, VOLO BEING IN CAMP BEFORE CELEBRATION)

Text.Value: NO! I mean to say - I am quite content behind bars. A precautionary measure, you understand.
The world will know my name. I don't need you for that.
What I owe? What are you talking about?
Your modesty does you credit, my fine friend. But bards and biographers need sordid details.
But I am engaged in celebration of the purest form - commemoration.
Away and have your fun! I have a myth to make.
They're quite dead now, as you know. Too dead to provide a single meaningful quote.

Synopsis:
Volo's dialog after the goblin hunt celebration party. Occurs whether tieflings or raiders win, with a variation for whether we've met Volo or not. This is his fallback in being added to our camp.

In the tiefling victory variation, Volo is sitting at his desk and thinking/writing an account of our victory that day. As we approach he should set down his pen and turn to speak with us, only returning to work again once he's dismissed us.

In the goblin victory celebration, Volo is standing in a cage much like the one in which he is placed in the goblin camp. In this case, he does not wish to be freed. He isn't writing anything or holding anything, but hands off his notes off-screen if intimidated into doing so.
